---

Based on your scope choices (MVP + pantry + OCR, all platforms, export-only sync, public-feed coupon prototype), this is feasible, but best delivered in staged releases to control risk. The current app already has reusable foundations for extraction, image handling, and dual storage in recipeExtractor.ts, ImageStorageService.ts, recipeDatabase.ts, and supabase.ts. The main gaps are new data models (recipe links, meal plans, pantry/shopping), OCR/document ingestion pipeline, and external feed normalization. Estimated timeline: 16–28 weeks solo, or 12–20 weeks with a 2–3 person team. Highest-risk area is coupons/sales data quality and ToS compliance; keep that as opt-in prototype after core premium value ships.

Feasibility & Difficulty

OCR scan from image/printed document + dish image capture: Feasible, Difficulty High
Recipe-to-recipe linking (component/sub-recipe): Feasible, Difficulty Medium
Meal planning + shopping list + pantry + Spoonacular assist: Feasible, Difficulty Medium-High
Email/external planning export (share + ICS): Feasible, Difficulty Low-Medium
Grocery sales/coupon public-feed prototype: Partially feasible, Difficulty High (data/compliance driven)
Steps

Define premium domain model and release slices in docs: update FEATURES.md and FUTURE_FEATURES.md with scope boundaries (what is in Phase 1/2/3).
Add schema for linked recipes, meal plans, meal plan entries, shopping items, pantry items, and feed offers in database_schema.sql plus migration files (same pattern as existing SQL migrations in repo root).
Extend app types and storage abstraction in supabase.ts and recipeDatabase.ts so every new entity supports Supabase + demo fallback.
Implement recipe-linking service and UI hooks in RecipeForm.tsx, RecipeViewer.tsx, and listing surfaces like RecipeList.tsx.
Add planner/pantry/shopping services and screens via Expo Router under app/(tabs)); update tabs in app/(tabs)/\_layout.tsx/\_layout.tsx) only for the exact MVP navigation needed.
Build OCR/document ingestion pipeline: replace OCR stub points in app/(tabs)/add.tsx/add.tsx#L103-L104) and app/(tabs)/add.tsx/add.tsx#L213-L215) with a real scan flow; route parsed content into existing form model in RecipeForm.tsx.
Reuse image infrastructure to store both recipe image and optional “dish photo” attachment through ImageStorageService.ts and SmartImage.tsx.
Add Spoonacular-assisted planning helpers in a new service adjacent to nutritionService.ts and webScrapingAPIService.ts, with strict quota/error fallback behavior.
Add export-only integration (email/share + ICS files) using existing share patterns from FavoritesList.tsx and RecipeViewer.tsx; avoid OAuth in this phase.
Implement grocery deals prototype as a separate service with public-feed ingestion, normalization, and feature flag; keep isolated from core planning so failures never block core flows.
Add premium gating + entitlement checks in premium entry points (based on current auth/navigation structure in \_layout.tsx and AuthContext.tsx).
Run staged QA across storage modes, platforms, and extraction paths using TESTING_CHECKLIST.md; then harden RLS/privacy policies before release.
Timeline

Phase 0 (1–2 w): Product/DB design, premium boundaries, migration plan
Phase 1 (3–5 w): Recipe linking + base planner + shopping list
Phase 2 (4–7 w): Pantry + Spoonacular planning assist
Phase 3 (4–8 w): OCR/image/document scan + dish image capture
Phase 4 (1–2 w): Export integrations (email/share + ICS)
Phase 5 (3–6 w): Public-feed deals/coupons prototype (behind feature flag)
Hardening/QA (2–4 w, overlapping): performance, edge cases, cross-platform polish
Verification

Data parity: validate every CRUD path in both Supabase and demo mode from recipeDatabase.ts
UX flow checks: add recipe by URL, by OCR scan, manual entry, then link recipes and add to meal plan
Planner outputs: generate shopping list from selected meal plan days and reconcile with pantry inventory
Export checks: verify email/share and ICS import into common calendar clients
Resilience: simulate API quota/timeouts for Spoonacular and feed outages; confirm graceful fallbacks
Decisions

Chose staged rollout over “all-at-once” to reduce rework and de-risk integrations.
Chose export-only external planning integration first (no OAuth), matching your selected sync depth.
Chose public-feed coupon prototype with isolation/feature flag to manage compliance and reliability risk.
